'''''Gridiron!''''' is a 1986 [[sports video game]] developed by [[Bethesda Softworks]] and published by [[Electronic Arts]]. The game was the first title of [[Maryland]] studio, founded by [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] graduate Christopher Weaver and lead programmer Ed Fletcher, who aimed to create a more realistic sports simulation title. 

==Gameplay==

''Gridiron!'' is a game in which statistics for players are provided on an NFL DataDisc.<ref name=CGW/>

== Development and release ==

''Gridiron!'' was developed by [[Bethesda Softworks]], a [[Bethesda, Maryland|Maryland]]-based studio created by founder [[Christopher Weaver]] in 1986.<ref>Ramsay (2012) p. 281</ref> Weaver created the game with lead programmer Ed Fletcher, a colleague in Weaver's former consulting company Media Technology who suggested entering the video game market.<ref>Ramsay (2012) p. 281, 285</ref> A football game was chosen as an initial project due to Fletcher's knowledge and interest in the game, with Weaver lacking knowledge of the game but having experience with physics and display interaction as a [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] science graduate.<ref>Ramsay (2012) p. 282</ref> Production was "extremely frugal" according to Weaver, with development taking place from his home in Bethesda. Developing the tools and physics engine from scratch, the developers aimed to address the problem of sports games of the time being limited in their potential to simulate reality.<ref>Ramsay (2012) p. 287</ref>

[[Electronic Arts]] entered an agreement with Bethesda Softworks to further market and distribute ''Gridiron!'' in return for developing a licensed [[John Madden]]  football title, a game that the publisher had been developing since 1984.<ref name=KT/> In 1988, Bethesda Softworks filed a $7.3 million lawsuit against the publisher on the claim that they had ceased release of ''Gridiron!'' to integrate major portions of the game into the Madden title.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Antic|volume=7|issue=5|date=September 1988|title=Late News Flashes|url=https://www.atarimagazines.com/v7n5/LateNewsFlashes.html|accessdate=31 March 2024}}</ref> An undisclosed sum was settled out of court.<ref>{{cite web|website=Polygon|title=A brief history of Bethesda’s many legal tangles|last=Campbell|first=Colin|date=28 June 2018|accessdate=31 March 2024|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/6/28/17511658/bethesda-lawsuits-fallout-elder-scrolls-prey}}</ref> Weaver retrospectively named the decision one of the "worst" made in his company,<ref name=WP/> considering Bethesda Softworks' contributions to its engine and technology to have "heavily influenced" its success.<ref>Ramsay (2012) p. 287</ref> [[John Madden Football (1988 video game)|John Madden Football]] was later published by Electronic Arts in 1988.

