''Gridiron!'' received generally positive reviews from critics. Writing for ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'', Wyatt Lee wrote that the game's custom playbooks and teams provided the potential for "tremendous constructability" and the "statistics critical" design was not often observed in football simulation games.<ref name=CGW>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/issues/cgw_42.pdf| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510161353/https://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/issues/cgw_42.pdf|last=Lee |first=Wyatt |title=The Electronic Gridiron |magazine=Computer Gaming World | archivedate=May 10, 2013| date=December 1987 |volume=1 |issue=42 |pages=17}}</ref> John Harrington of ''[[Games International]]'' considered the game to be an impressive mixture of strategy and arcade play.<ref name=GI>{{cite journal | url=https://archive.org/details/GamesInternational/GI_13_FebMar_1990/page/n51/mode/2up| last = Harrington |first = John | title =Gridiron! | journal = [[Games International]] | issue = 13 | pages =52–3 |date=February–March 1990}}</ref> Andy Eddy for ''Atari Explorer'' found the Atari title to be challenging and enjoyable with a "strategically accurate" design, commenting that whilst the minimal graphics assisted with seeing how formations and plays evolve, the graphics were not of a high standard.<ref name=AE/> Ervin Bobo of ''Compute!'' noted the game's customisation abilities presented "options never before seen" in a football simulation, finding the simplified graphics was "no handicap" to the gameplay.<ref name=CP>{{cite magazine|magazine=Compute!|issue=85|date=June 1987|last=Bobo|first=Ervin|pages=57|title=Gridiron!|url=https://archive.org/details/1987-06-compute-magazine/page/56}}</ref> Bob Ryan of ''Amiga World Magazine'' commended the title as an "excellent physical simulation" and the "best game" played on the Amiga, although acknowledging the "simple but not crude" graphics.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Amiga World|title=Gridiron!|last=Ryan|first=Bob|date=March 1987|pages=90|url=https://archive.org/details/amiga-world-1987-03/page/n91}}</ref> Uwe Rönitz for ''Amiga Joker'' considered the Amiga version to be appealing and playable, although noting the game took time to get used to with the difficulty "high demands" on the user.<ref name=AM/> However, Torsten Blum for ''[[Aktueller Software Markt]]'' dismissed the Amiga version of the game as a "failed sports-strategy hybrid" and "lousy simulator", citing the lack of game options, the "spartan" graphics and "monotonous" gameplay.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Aktueller Software Markt|last=Blum|first=Torsten|pages=86|title=Certainly Not a Touchdown!|language=DE|date=January 1990|url=https://archive.org/details/asm_magazine-1990-01/page/n85}}</ref>

The game sold well<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Ginsburg|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/85238442/fort-worth-star-telegram/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20210913043936/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/85238442/fort-worth-star-telegram/|title=Computer experts, hockey coach team up to create realistic video games|newspaper=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]|archivedate=September 13, 2021|date=January 9, 1994|accessdate=July 19, 2021|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>  and was awarded Sports game of the year,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/game-pro-uk-07/page/70/mode/2up|title=Bethesda A brief History|magazine=[[GamePro]]|date=March 1996|accessdate=July 12, 2021}}</ref><ref name="publisher">{{cite web|url=http://www.bethsoft.com/html/about2.html|title=Bethesda Softworks History|publisher=bethsoft.com|accessdate=July 20, 2021|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970605103153/http://www.bethsoft.com/html/about2.html|archivedate=June 5, 1997}}</ref> as well as voted as one of the 40 Best Games of All Time by [[Amiga World]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/85238527/the-record/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20220123132328/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/85238527/the-record/|title=Dare to Face Off with "The Great One"|newspaper=[[The Record (North Jersey)|The Record]]|archivedate=January 23, 2022|date=December 5, 1989|accessdate=August 16, 2021|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>  Bethesda founder [[Christopher Weaver]] said in 1994 that ''Gridiron'' "put us on the map"<ref>{{cite news|first=Rick|last=Snider|url=https://archive.org/details/document-the-washington-times-archives-3|title=Putting Future in play:Games as door to new worlds Virtual Reality is Newton in a box to founder of software firm|page=C12|newspaper=[[The Washington Times]]|date=March 10, 1994|accessdate=March 2, 2023}}</ref> and In 1995 Weaver said that the game was the best-selling sports game ever published for Atari ST and Amiga.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://imgur.com/a/a0Tsu|title=Bethesda Softworks the litle giant|magazine=[[PC Gamer]]|date=November 1995|accessdate=February 3, 2024|archive-date=February 5, 2024|archive-url=https://archive.today/20240205033647/https://imgur.com/a/a0Tsu|url-status=bot: unknown}}</ref>

=== Retrospective reception ===

Several critics have retrospectively praised ''Gridiron'' for its technical innovation and subsequent influence upon the [[Madden Football]] series. Rick Maese of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' described the game as "unremarkable for its stone-age graphics but ahead of its time for the physics and coding that laid the technical groundwork for sports titles to follow".<ref name=WP>{{cite web|website=The Washington Post|last=Maese|first=Rick|date=9 August 2018|title=This forgotten video game helped pave the way for Madden NFL|accessdate=31 March 2024|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/sports/wp/2018/08/09/this-forgotten-video-game-helped-pave-the-way-for-madden-nfl/}}</ref> Tyler Wilde of ''[[PC Gamer]]'' described the simulation mechanics as an "unheard of feat" for its time.<ref>{{cite web|website=PC Gamer|last=Wilde|first=Tyler|title=The games that defined Bethesda, from 1986 to the Microsoft acquisition|date=11 March 2021|accessdate=31 March 2024|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/bethesda-important-games/}}</ref> Luke Plunkett of ''Kotaku'' similarly noted the game's simulation mechanics were "unheard of" and the first time "true physics" were integrated into sports gaming, whilst assessing the game to by "ugly" even by the standards of the time.<ref name=KT>{{cite web|website=Kotaku|last=Plunkett|first=Luke|date=3 February 2019|title=Before Elder Scrolls, Bethesda Helped Create Madden|accessdate=31 March 2024|url=https://kotaku.com/before-elder-scrolls-bethesda-helped-create-madden-5816920}}</ref> 

